commercial proofing tools represent only a subset of errors that a non-native speaker might make.
			For example, while many non-native speakers may encounter difficulty choosing among prepositions, this is typically not a significant problem for native speakers and hence remains unaddressed in proofing tools such as the grammar checker in Microsoft Word (Heidorn 2000).
			Plainly there is an opening here for automated proofing tools that are better geared to the non-native users.
			One challenge that automated proofing tools face is that writing errors often present a semantic dimension that renders it difficult if not impossible to provide a single correct suggestion.
			The choice of definite versus indefinite determiner?a common error type among writers with a Japanese, Chinese or Korean language background owing to the lack of overt markers for definiteness and indefiniteness?is highly dependent on larger textual context and world knowledge.
